01:08:15,602 --> 01:08:15,983
[SPEAKER_06]: Hey, Todd?

837
01:08:16,603 --> 01:08:16,823
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

838
01:08:17,898 --> 01:08:21,561
[SPEAKER_06]: Today parking is allowed on both sides to understand that correctly.

839
01:08:22,662 --> 01:08:38,894
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, in the traffic commission records is no regulation restricting it accepts down with that red dot is near the hydrant parking, but so for whatever reason the historical use of this area.

840
01:08:39,605 --> 01:08:42,566
[SPEAKER_04]: the vehicles park all four wheels on the sidewalk even though.

841
01:08:43,346 --> 01:08:46,647
[SPEAKER_04]: Which I think in and of itself is against the rules, is it not?

842
01:08:46,987 --> 01:08:47,887
[SPEAKER_04]: Correct.

843
01:08:51,769 --> 01:08:56,450
[SPEAKER_04]: We're really not voting on the sidewalk necessarily at the commission because it's already an existing rule.

844
01:08:57,130 --> 01:09:06,773
[SPEAKER_04]: It's because we're going to inform people that we're going to start to enforce that, we're explaining to them what it is available to them.

845
01:09:07,632 --> 01:09:14,859
[SPEAKER_04]: which we're allowing some in the street on that side and restricting other areas in the street, formally restricting other areas.

846
01:09:16,380 --> 01:09:28,712
[SPEAKER_04]: Because if we allow parking on both sides with no yellow arrows as restricted zones, then someone's going to come off Fells Way and back into Fells Way if someone's coming up at them because there's not enough width to pass each other.

847
01:09:29,667 --> 01:09:49,526
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, so instead of just saying you can't park on this block on the side, so keeping it to one side, we're going to allow these small pieces because you can't, it sounds like from a geometric standpoint, have parking on both sides and have that street function the way we want.

848
01:09:49,886 --> 01:09:53,210
[SPEAKER_06]: So people are kicking up onto the sidewalk and that's been allowed for years.

849
01:09:56,278 --> 01:09:57,119
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, essentially.

850
01:09:57,159 --> 01:10:07,406
[SPEAKER_04]: So if a car parks directly opposite one another on this block or the middle block, then only one car could pass at a time, correct?

851
01:10:08,247 --> 01:10:09,408
[SPEAKER_04]: And it's a two-way street.

852
01:10:10,569 --> 01:10:12,590
[SPEAKER_04]: But again, we want it to be somewhat consistent.

853
01:10:12,630 --> 01:10:20,476
[SPEAKER_04]: This middle block has parking on both sides with that caveat that only physically one vehicle could pass at a time, but there's enough driveways.

854
01:10:21,837 --> 01:10:22,658
[SPEAKER_04]: So we're trying to be...

855
01:10:23,319 --> 01:10:25,221
[SPEAKER_04]: We'll see if this works.

856
01:10:25,261 --> 01:10:32,790
[SPEAKER_04]: If it presents a safety issue, then we'd probably come back with one whole site restricted.

857
01:10:35,033 --> 01:10:36,134
[SPEAKER_01]: So one thing that I've

858
01:10:37,376 --> 01:10:45,340
[SPEAKER_01]: Wondered about is so where the driveways are, it provides a gap for somebody to par to pull out.

859
01:10:45,800 --> 01:10:47,681
[SPEAKER_01]: But my thought is that if somebody was.

860
01:10:48,161 --> 01:10:52,563
[SPEAKER_01]: The street is so narrow that if somebody is parked right behind somebody's driveway.

861
01:10:53,263 --> 01:10:55,704
[SPEAKER_01]: They won't be able to pull out of their driveway.

862
01:10:55,744 --> 01:10:57,345
[SPEAKER_01]: They would hit the car across the street.

863
01:10:58,045 --> 01:11:10,630
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know if that's true or just my guessing and whether these yellow spots that the not allowed spots are positioned to be in line with where the driveways are so people can back out of their driveways.

864
01:11:13,348 --> 01:11:30,178
[SPEAKER_01]: If you look at Google Maps right now, you can see a couple of different examples of vehicles parked right up on the sidewalk, and the sidewalk actually painted in a way to show people where they can't park so that people can get in the pedestrian path.

